  "prompt": "Where can I study at Stanford?",
  "response": "Stanford University offers a plethora of amazing study spots, catering to different learning styles. Here's a breakdown of some popular and lesser-known options, categorized for your convenience:\n\n**Libraries (Extensive Resources & Quiet Study):**\n\n*   **Green Library (Main Library):** This is the big one. Green Library is the largest and most comprehensive library at Stanford. It features:\n    *   **Bing Wing:** A magnificent space with high ceilings and stained glass windows, perfect for focused work.\n    *   **East Wing:** Offers a mix of individual study carrels and group study rooms.\n    *   **Graduate Study Room:** A quiet area dedicated to graduate students.\n    *   **Various reading rooms:** Dedicated to specific subject areas.\n*   **Terman Engineering Library:** Geared towards engineering and science students. Has study areas, computers, and research resources.\n*   **Lane Medical Library:** For those in the medical field. Offers a comprehensive collection of medical resources and study spaces.\n*   **Crown Law Library:** Focused on law materials and study areas for law students.\n*   **Cubberley Education Library:** Specializes in education resources and provides a supportive environment for education students.\n*   **Art & Architecture Library:** Houses a vast collection of art and architecture books, journals, and resources, as well as spaces for individual and group study.\n*   **East Asia Library:** Rich in resources related to East Asian studies, with quiet study areas for focused research.\n\n**Student Union & Academic Buildings (Convenient & Social):**\n\n*   **Stanford Student Union (Old Union & Tresidder):**\n    *   **Coffee shops (e.g., CoHo, Starbucks):** Good for a more casual atmosphere.\n    *   **Meeting rooms:** Can sometimes be booked for group study.\n    *   **Outdoor patios:** Great for studying in good weather.\n*   **Academic Buildings (Specific to your Major):** Check the buildings where your classes are held. Many departments have common areas, lounges, or study rooms for their students. Popular options include:\n    *   **Huang Engineering Center:** Offers various study areas and collaboration spaces.\n    *   **Gates Computer Science Building:** Has lounges and study areas for computer science students.\n    *   **History Corner:** A classic spot with benches and lawns for outdoor study.\n    *   **Math Corner:** Similar to History Corner, but for math students.\n*   **Lorry I. Lokey Stem Cell Research Building:** Provides an environment that inspires collaboration, equipped with a modern caf\u00e9, lounge, and group study rooms.\n*   **Knight Management Center (GSB):** If you have a connection to the business school, their facilities are top-notch.\n\n**Outdoor Spaces (When the Weather is Nice):**\n\n*   **Main Quad:** A beautiful and iconic space for studying outdoors on the grass or benches.\n*   **Memorial Church Lawn:** Another picturesque spot near a landmark.\n*   **Rodin Sculpture Garden:** A serene and inspiring place to study amidst art.\n*   **Arizona Garden (Cactus Garden):** A unique and quiet place to study with a variety of cacti and succulents.\n*   **White Plaza:** Plenty of seating and a lively atmosphere.\n*   **The Oval:** A large grassy area perfect for spreading out a blanket and studying.\n*   **Lake Lagunita (when it has water):** A scenic spot to study by the water.\n\n**Other Considerations:**\n\n*   **Your Dorm Room:** A private and convenient option.\n*   **Residential Lounges:** Each dorm has its own lounge, which can be a good place to study with friends.\n*   **EVGR (Escondido Village Graduate Residences):** Has common areas and study spaces specifically for graduate students.\n*   **Off-Campus Cafes:** Palo Alto and nearby towns have numerous cafes with good study vibes.\n\n**Tips for Finding the Best Spot:**\n\n*   **Consider your learning style:** Do you need quiet or background noise? Do you prefer to study alone or with others?\n*   **Think about your needs:** Do you need access to computers, printers, or specific resources?\n*   **Try different places:** Experiment with different locations until you find a few that work for you.\n*   **Check the hours:** Make sure the location is open when you want to study.\n*   **Use the Stanford Libraries website:** It provides information on all the libraries, including hours, resources, and services.\n*   **Ask around:** Talk to other students and ask them for their favorite study spots.\n\nNo matter what your preference, Stanford offers a diverse range of study environments to support your academic success. Good luck finding your perfect spot!\n",
